Bring a large #pot{} of water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Heat a large dry pan over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce}; cook, turning occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy, ~{6-10%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a paper-towel-lined plate.

Carefully discard all but a thin layer of bacon fat from pan.

Once bacon is cool enough to handle, roughly chop.

While bacon cooks, peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Peel and mince @onion{1}.

Return pan with reserved bacon fat to medium heat. Add garlic, a pinch of @chili flakes{1/4%teaspoon}, and @pepper{} (if pan seems dry, add a drizzle of @olive oil{}). Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Add onion; season with @salt{1 1/2%tsp}. Cook, stirring frequently, until softened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Add @crushed tomatoes{13.76%ounce}, bacon, and @sugar{0.13%teaspoon}; bring to a simmer and cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce has thickened, ~{12-15%minutes} more.

Once sauce has simmered ~{4-5%minutes}, add @spaghetti{6%ounce} to pot of boiling water. Cook, stirring occasionally, until just al dente, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Add drained spaghetti and 1/2 cup reserved pasta cooking water to pan with sauce; cook, tossing occasionally, until pasta is evenly coated, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> If needed, stir in more pasta cooking water a splash at a time.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide pasta between bowls. Sprinkle with @parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon} and remaining @chili flakes{3/4%teaspoon} if desired. Serve.

> Bacon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.